The result of such an object detection CNN is a set of bounding boxes. Each bounding box, specified by location in the image and size, has also probability values for each detectable object class attached. In figure \ref{obj detection} a typical result of the object detection is shown. In this image only the most likely detections are displayed. As one can see the result is far from perfect, even with state-of-the-art object detection CNNs. Many objects are not detected or have a low confidence. Another problem visible in the image is the possibility of overlapping bounding boxes. These problems have to be taken into account in the design of the object mapping system, as the accumulation of information from multiple images is needed for more reliable results.

\begin{figure}[h]
  \includegraphics[width=1.0\textwidth]{figures/vision_still.png}
  \caption[Example result of room type classification and object detection]{A typical result of the object detection and the place recognition; detections with a probability greater than $0.1$ are shown with bounding box, most likely class and its probability; in the upper left corner of the image the top classifications of the place classifier and their probabilities are shown} 
  \label{obj detection}
\end{figure}

Alongside with the color image the RGBD-camera takes also an depth image, which contains depth measurements for every pixel. Due to technical limitations the depth of some pixels cannot be measured and are marked as invalid. Combining the position of the pixel, the depth value and the intrinsic camera parameters the position of the pixel in space can be calculated. Projecting a bounding box into 3D space on the other hand is not meaningful as neighboring pixels in the image are not necessarily nearby in 3D. The approximate location of a detected object can be estimated using the median depth in the bounding box. However, the extend of an object is difficult to estimate, therefore a sample-based approach is used. A sufficient number of pixels with valid depth values is drawn randomly from the image. Each of those samples holds an object probability for every object class. The problem is that bounding boxes also contain pixels not belonging to the object and pixels can be within multiple bounding boxes. Per-pixel segmentation of detected objects is an option to solve this problem, but segmentation is costly for large numbers of detections and wrong segmentations are possible, especially with small or complex objects, overlapping bounding boxes and occlusion. Therefore simply the maximum object probability of all bounding boxes overlapping a pixel is used. The idea behind this is the assumption that all bounding boxes with lower probabilities are just accidentally overlapping. The unreliability of this approach is then taken into account in the inverse sensor model of the object mapping. 

Ultimately, the result of the object detection is a set of 3D points, each one holding probabilities for every detectable object types. Furthermore, the result contains object type and estimated 3D location of very confident object detections. 

\subsection{Room Type Classification} %TODO reference to Places-205?

In this thesis room type c

Various features can be used for room type classification, like 
Visual input and the shape and size of the room can be used for the classification. In this thesis the detection is only done throug the visual input of the roboter cameras because outgoing from visual features of the images it is possible to classify the room. The shape and size of the room can help by the detection but this data are not sufficient for the classification and only a limited amount of data is available. For the calssification throug images datasets with millions of labeled images are freely accessable. One example is the MIT Places-205 Dataset which contains about 2.5 million images assigned to 205 place categories. CNNs trained on this dataset are publicly availabe and are used in this thesis. 

There are various features which can be used to classify rooms into categories used by humans. In this work this is done solely using visual input. Visual features are very expressive for room classification and also image datasets containing lots of labeled images exist. Other features like shape or size are not used because of their limited expressiveness and the limited data available. The MIT Places-205 Dataset contains about 2.5 million images assigned to 205 place categories and CNNs trained on this dataset are publicly available. Ignoring outdoor place categories this leaves 60 indoor room types, which are listed in table \ref{room types}. The result of the CNN is a probability distribution over the 205 place categories. The outdoor categories are ignored by setting their probabilities to zero. The remaining probabilities are then normalized to one, resulting in a probability distribution over the 60 indoor categories for the room type seen in the input image.


